Insider hacking

If you hack into a company=E2=80=99s computers and steal its earnings
release before it=E2=80=99s public, and then you trade the company=E2=80=99=
s stock based on
the earnings release, is that insider trading? There is an argument that it
isn=E2=80=99t: You are not an *insider*, you had no duty of trust and confi=
dence to
the company, you just hacked into its computers and stole inside
information. By the letter of the Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=
=99s insider
trading rule
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xMGI1LTE/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBf375e3ed>,
it would seem that you are not guilty of insider trading.

My slightly more expansive view of the matter is that =E2=80=9Cinsider trad=
ing=E2=80=9D
means (1) trading on material nonpublic information that (2) you got in a
bad way. Getting material nonpublic information by hacking is clearly a bad
way to get it, so you insider traded. This is, I think, fairly intuitive.
We have talked a couple
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDQtMDEvYW5vdGhlci1wb2x=
pdGljaWFuLXdhbnRzLXRvLWJhbi1pbnNpZGVyLXRyYWRpbmc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
18d4ff7>
of times
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTItMDYvZ3JlZW4tYm9uZHM=
td2l0aG91dC10aGUtYm9uZHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd385385>
about an insider trading bill that has been proposed in Congress and passed
the House of Representatives that uses this intuitive standard (=E2=80=9Cob=
tained
wrongfully=E2=80=9D), but it is not yet the law.

So it=E2=80=99s a bit murky but, you know, don=E2=80=99t actually do this. =
Even if it is
not =E2=80=9Cinsider trading,=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99re gonna get in trouble =
for it. Insider trading
is not a separate crime; it is a variety of securities fraud, a violation
of Section 10(b)
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc4ag/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B25ef30ed>
of the Exchange Act, which prohibits using =E2=80=9Cany manipulative or dec=
eptive
device=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cin connection with the purchase or sale of any sec=
urity,=E2=80=9D and of Rule
10b-5
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xMGItNQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBb95189c5>,
which prohibits using =E2=80=9Cany device, scheme, or artifice to defraud =
=E2=80=A6 in
connection with the purchase or sale of any security.=E2=80=9D Insider trad=
ing is
just treated as a kind of =E2=80=9Cmanipulative or deceptive device.=E2=80=
=9D But so is
hacking, probably. If it=E2=80=99s not insider trading, it=E2=80=99s exactl=
y as bad as
insider trading and prohibited by exactly the same statute.

We talked
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDgtMTEvd2h5LW5vdC1pbnN=
pZGVyLXRyYWRlLW9uLWV2ZXJ5LWNvbXBhbnkt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5234bf45>
way back in 2015 about some hackers who hacked into the news wires =E2=80=
=94 the
services that store companies=E2=80=99 press releases before they are relea=
sed
=E2=80=94 and got thousands of earnings releases early, and then sold those
earnings releases to traders who used them to make money. =E2=80=9CBig hack=
er
insider trading charges,=E2=80=9D I called them. Were they? Two traders wer=
e
convicted of securities fraud based on this, and they appealed, and on
Monday the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit decided the appeals
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuY2EyLnVzY291cnRzLmdvdi9sbi8xOS0xOTdfb3BuLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Ba33f9f19>.[1]
One of the traders argued that he could not have committed securities fraud=
:

To challenge his convictions on these substantive securities fraud counts,
Korchevsky first argues that the government could not prove he engaged in a
=E2=80=9Cscheme or artifice to defraud=E2=80=9D within the meaning of Rule =
10b-5.
Specifically, he claims the proof necessarily failed because he did not owe
a fiduciary duty to investors or potential investors in the companies whose
press releases were stolen, and because any deception employed to obtain
the releases did not target the investors. Second, Korchevsky argues that
the type of computer hacking used to access Marketwired=E2=80=99s systems=
=E2=80=94the
conduct charged in Count Four=E2=80=94did not constitute a =E2=80=9Cdecepti=
ve device or
contrivance=E2=80=9D within the meaning of Section 10(b).

The Second Circuit disagreed:

First, we dispatch Korchevsky=E2=80=99s contention that he did not engage i=
n a
=E2=80=9Cscheme or artifice to defraud.=E2=80=9D Although a fiduciary duty =
is relevant to
other securities violations=E2=80=94e.g., insider trading=E2=80=94it need n=
ot be shown to
prove the securities fraud charged here: fraudulent trading in securities
by an outsider. Further, Korchevsky=E2=80=99s assertion that the deception =
must
have targeted investors contradicts the plain language of Rule 10b-5. The
deception need only be =E2=80=9Cin connection with the purchase or sale of =
any
security,=E2=80=9D and here it was. The newswire hacking directly prompted =
and
enabled the charged securities trading. Indeed, the ensuing trades needed
to occur soon after a press release was illicitly obtained from a
newswire=E2=80=99s servers, but before the newswire could publish the relea=
se, in
order to maximize the hacked information=E2=80=99s value.

Second, we find that the hack of Marketwired=E2=80=99s systems qualified as=
 a
=E2=80=9Cdeceptive device or contrivance=E2=80=9D under Section 10(b). ... =
Every time the
hackers attempted to access parts of the system by entering stolen
credentials, they misrepresented themselves to be authorized users.
=E2=80=9C[M]isrepresenting one=E2=80=99s identity in order to gain access t=
o information
that is otherwise off limits, and then stealing that information is plainly
=E2=80=98deceptive=E2=80=99 within the ordinary meaning of the word.=E2=80=
=9D

The logic there feels a little strange =E2=80=94 they deceived *Marketwired=
*, which
allowed them to make money from *investors*; all in all they did securities
fraud, but don=E2=80=99t ask *who *they defrauded =E2=80=94 until you remem=
ber that it=E2=80=99s
exactly the logic of insider trading. =E2=80=9CInsider trading is not about
fairness, it=E2=80=99s about theft,=E2=80=9D I often
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMTMveW91LWhhdmUtdG8=
tcGF5LXRoZS1yaWdodC1wZXJzb24/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB50f3cb5f>
say
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMTAtMDUvanVzdGljZXMtYXJ=
lbi10LWludGVyZXN0ZWQtaW4taW5zaWRlci10cmFkaW5nLWNhc2U/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB524fb16d>:
In insider trading, you get in trouble for the combination of (1) betraying
your duty of confidence to the owner of the information (your employer,
your golf buddy
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTQtMDgtMTgvb25lLWdvbGYtY29=
1cnNlLXRoYXQtcy1ncmVhdC1mb3Itc3RvY2stdGlwcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd8deea=
a9>,
etc.) and (2) using the information to make money by trading stock with
strangers. You are I suppose doing a securities fraud on the people who
trade with you, but you=E2=80=99re not really deceiving them; it=E2=80=99s =
the combination
of betraying one person and making money from another that creates insider
trading. Same with hacking-based insider trading. Which I am going to
continue to call =E2=80=9Cinsider trading=E2=80=9D even if the Second Circu=
it doesn=E2=80=99t.
Wall Street culture

My shameful secret vice is I basically agree with this
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjAvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtanB=
tb3JnYW4tZXhlYy1zYXlzLXdoeS1iYW5rZXJzLW5lZWQtdG8td29yay03Mi1ob3Vycy1hLXdlZW=
s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfabd16c6>
:

There=E2=80=99s a reason junior bankers just starting out on Wall Street wo=
rk
12-hour days, six days a week, says Mary Erdoes, chief executive officer of
JPMorgan Chase & Co.=E2=80=99s asset and wealth management business. ... In=
 an
episode of =E2=80=9CBloomberg Wealth with David Rubenstein,=E2=80=9D she in=
voked the
concept that it takes 10,000 hours of practice and devotion to compete at
an elite level.

=E2=80=9CIf you think 10,000 hours is about what you need to master any sub=
ject, if
someone comes in and has a regular, eight-hour-a-day job, five days a week,
it=E2=80=99s gonna take about five years to have a base-level mastery,=E2=
=80=9D she said to
Rubenstein, the co-founder of Carlyle Group, on Bloomberg TV. =E2=80=9COn W=
all
Street, it=E2=80=99s more like 12 hours a day, six days a week. That cuts y=
ou down
to about two and a half years before you become mastered in something.=E2=
=80=9D

Yeah it=E2=80=99s fine. I think you probably do get better, faster, at maki=
ng
leveraged buyout models if you do it 80 hours a week instead of 40 hours a
week, and that is useful both for you and for your employer.

I also think, though, that there is a signaling benefit to it that is
almost detached from the content. If you go to Wall Street and spend two
years working 80 or 100-hour weeks building LBO models, and everyone knows
that that=E2=80=99s how it works, then people will assume that your
LBO-model-building skills are impressive. Not just that you=E2=80=99re good=
 at
building LBO models, I mean, but also that that=E2=80=99s a fancy skill to =
have.
=E2=80=9COh, wow, you have mastered a skill that requires years of grueling=
 labor
and total commitment,=E2=80=9D they will say. Then they will hire you for s=
ome job
that *doesn=E2=80=99t *require building LBO models, because they assume tha=
t you=E2=80=99re
smart and knowledgeable, or they will pay *your bank *lots of money to
advise on their merger, because they assume that the bank has arcane and
hard-to-acquire skills. Whereas if you spent 40 hours a week building LBO
models everyone would be like =E2=80=9Cmeh that can=E2=80=99t be that hard.=
=E2=80=9D None of this
has anything to do with what goes into an LBO model; it=E2=80=99s just abou=
t the
hours that you (ostentatiously) work.

I have written recently
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMTIvZ29sZG1hbi1kb2V=
zbi10LXdhbnQtbWVyY2VuYXJpZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaca93f6f>
about the tension between the old model of Wall Street analyst programs as
sort of a universal finishing school for smart ambitious people, versus a
gentler model of Wall Street analyst programs as just a normal job. If it=
=E2=80=99s
an elite finishing school =E2=80=94 like a medical residency =E2=80=94 then=
 I suppose it
should be 80 hours a week; becoming elite is hard, and not for just anyone.
If it=E2=80=99s just a job then, you know, sure, take the weekend off, play=
 a sport
<https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24514165.265021/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjAvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4=
tcy10aHJlZS1zcGFjcy13ZXJlLXRvby1tYW55/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe7dfce42>,
whatever. I think that if you are entering a Wall Street analyst program,
you probably want to take the weekend off (I sure do!), but also want it to
retain its mystique as an elite finishing school. Those things are in
tension.
